== Projects \n

*Distributed Sequential Detection* \n
With the rising need for robust detection in real life systems and the usage of power hungry and energy consuming sensors, there's always the 
need for reaching a decision or deciding on a hypothesis in the quickest way and in the process making an optimal number of observations which guarantee the performance in terms of the pre-specified probabilities of error. 
In a large scale dynamical system where agents collaborate among themselves(in their one-hop neighbourhood) in contrast with that of the optimal centralised setting where agents transmit high dimensional data to a fusion centre, 
a sequential detection algorithm makes a lot of savings as far 
as the number of observations is concerned.
We proposed a distributed sequential probability ratio test (SPRT) type algorithm, in which the agents update their decision 
statistics by simultaneously processing local observations (innovations) sensed sequentially over time and information obtained 
from neighboring agents (consensus). For each pre-specified set of type I and type II error probabilities, we not only proved the 
existence of local detection thresholds but also derived them under some mild conditioning which ensure that the algorithm achieves 
the desired error performance and terminates in finite time almost surely (a.s.). We also quantified the ratio of expected number of 
observations for the distributed setup and the centralised setup in asymptotics of the vanishing error metrics in terms of the network connectivity.
