*Distributed Composite Hypothesis Testing* \n
Most works on hypothesis testing in literature, consider either binary simple hypotheses or multiple simple hypotheses. 
To the best of our knowledge, schemes which consider composite hypothesis and that too in a fully distributed setup have not been addressed 
in the literature till now. Hence, we study the problem of a recursive Gaussian composite hypothesis test in a network of sparsely interconnected agents, 
in which an agent observes a small portion of the field which emulates all the parametric alternatives. Two recursive generalized likelihood ratio test (GLRT) 
type algorithms in a distributed framework, of the consensus-plus-innovations form are proposed, in which the agents estimate the underlying parameter and also 
in a parallel fashion update their decision statistics by simultaneously processing latest estimate of the parameter and information obtained from neighboring 
agents. Under a very general non-linear observation model and weak global observability, consistency of the parameter estimate, asymptotic normality of the 
decision statistic and algorithm parameters which ensure asymptotically (in the large sample limit) decaying probabilities of errors are established. 
In a separate algorithm, we consider a linear observation model and under weak global observability, apart from establishing consistency of the parameter 
estimate, we characterize the large deviations exponents for the probabilities of the errors. Finally, simulation studies are presented which illustrate and 
verify the analytical findings.
